{"parse":{"title":"Kerateion","pageid":22485800,"revid":697260617,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Kerateion</b><sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> (<a href=\"/wiki/Greek_language\" title=\"Greek language\">Greek</a>: <span lang=\"el\">\u039a\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u1fd6\u03bf\u03bd</span>) was the <a href=\"/wiki/Jewish_quarter_(diaspora)\" title=\"Jewish quarter (diaspora)\">Jewish quarter</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Seleucid\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Seleucid\">Seleucid</a> capital (and later Roman-Syrian capital) of <a href=\"/wiki/Antioch_on_the_Orontes\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Antioch on the Orontes\">Antioch on the Orontes</a>.  The suburb was located in the southern portion of the ancient city, situated between the Forum Colonnades of Herod and <a href=\"/wiki/Taurus_Mountains\" title=\"Taurus Mountains\">Mt. Tauris</a>, a rocky crag at the foot of Mount Silpios.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The city of Antioch was erected around 300 BC by <a href=\"/wiki/Seleucus_I_Nicator\" title=\"Seleucus I Nicator\">Seleucus I Nicator</a>.  After defeating the General Antigones and taking the city also called Antigones, Seleucus built a new city and named it after his Father Antiochos, a General who served under Alexander.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Seleucus then populated the city with Macedonians, Inhabitants of the recently conquered city, Antigones, and Jews. The Jewish population had a special, independent relationship with Seleucid dynasty and even had bronze plaques erected to codify their autonomous standing.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>According to Glanville Downey, Kerateion was situated in the southern end of the city between the Cherubim Gate from the first century and the newer Daphne Gate on the bank of the torrent called Phyrminus (across from the present barracks). If this is correct the situation will be close to the present <a href=\"/wiki/Synagogue\" title=\"Synagogue\">synagogue</a> in the opposite direction of Mount Staurin where St. Peter's Grotto is located.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Kerateion&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://libaniusredux.blogspot.com/2009/03/jewish-quarters.html\">http://libaniusredux.blogspot.com/2009/03/jewish-quarters.html</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.reu.org/public/chrysos/life.txt\">http://www.reu.org/public/chrysos/life.txt</a> \u2013 Section 32</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>A Short History of Antioch</i> (1921), Chapter 2, page 20</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>A Short History of Antioch</i>,  Chapter 5, page 105</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Downey, G.: <i>A History of Antioch in Syria</i>, Princeton 1961, p. 615</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2222\nCached time: 20180922102727\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.164 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.185 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 75/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 240/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 0/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 3/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1681/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.138/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 8.78 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%  165.065      1 Template:Lang-el\n100.00%  165.065      1 -total\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:22485800-0!canonical and timestamp 20180922102726 and revision id 697260617\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"Articles_containing_Greek-language_text"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Ancient_Antioch"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Historic_Jewish_communities"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Antioch on the Orontes"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Greek language"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Jewish quarter (diaspora)"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Seleucid"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Seleucus I Nicator"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Synagogue"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Taurus Mountains"}],"templates":[{"ns":10,"exists":"","*":"Template:Lang-el"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"Module:Lang"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"Module:No globals"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"Module:Arguments"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"Module:Language/name/data"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"Module:Language/data/iana languages"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"Module:Language/data/ISO 639-3"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"Module:Language/data/wp languages"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"Module:Language/data/iana scripts"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"M